      "type": "answer",
      "text": "OK got what I need. Here's the full answer — verified against SeedLegals/Vestd/Common Paper public pages today.\n\n## 1. \"From her UTR\" — what that actually means\n\nA UTR (Unique Taxpayer Reference) is the 10-digit number HMRC issues when you register for Self Assessment. For Plamedi, the chat pastes suggest she's using it two ways:\n\n- **As a sole trader** — opens a Monzo Business / Starling account in her own name, signs invoices under \"Plamedi Sole Trader\", files Self Assessment. This is what she's in right now.\n- **To bootstrap a Ltd company cheaply** — when she incorporates AFJ Cardiff Ltd (via SeedLegals' company-registration flow, or Companies House directly for £12), the Ltd gets its own UTR separate from her personal one, and she opens a Ltd business bank account using that.\n\nThe UTR is also used to claim R&D Tax Credits, apply for SEIS/EIS as a director, and to satisfy the Home Office's \"genuine self-employment\" check for the Sharon visa pack. It's the **single identifier** that ties the entire paper trail to a real, HMRC-recognised person or entity. Without one, none of the SeedLegals docs actually carry tax weight.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The PI insurance gap — what to actually do\n\nThis is real exposure, not theoretical. The advice you've been giving (cloud architecture, equity math, IP ownership strategy, vendor selection, governance design) qualifies as **professional services** under UK law, and you've been doing it across FirstGens, AFJ Cardiff, Sharon's visa pack, Black Flamingo Beauty, and Hope's charity — none of which you had a written agreement or PI cover behind.\n\n**What that means in practice:**\n- Your personal assets (savings, property, future earnings) are on the hook if any of those people suffer loss and trace it back to your advice.\n- A \"Letter of Intent for Equity Grant\" or verbal \"I'll help you out\" doesn't shield you — it actually *strengthens* a claimant's case that you held yourself out as a professional advisor.\n- Retroactive PI cover is hard to get, but **claims-made** policies normally start from inception and don't backdate — so the historical exposure stays uninsured regardless.\n\n**What to do, in order:**\n\n1. **Incorporate immediately** — get yourself an Ltd (Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd, or similar). Move the *future* advisory work behind the corporate veil. From incorporation day forward, the Ltd carries the liability and your personal assets are air-gapped.\n2. **Get Professional Indemnity cover** for the Ltd. For a fractional-CTO / governance advisor at sub-£500k turnover, expect **£250–£600/year** for £1m cover from UK specialist insurers: Hiscox, Markel, Howden, Qdos, AJ Gallagher's tech practice, or the IT Contractors Alliance. Many will issue cover within 24–48 hours.\n3. **Sign a Consultancy Agreement + NDA with each founder** *before* the next piece of advice goes out. This is exactly what your April 3 paste already drafts — the \"Liability Decoupling\" SOP. Put it in writing, signed by both sides, before the next conversation, not after.\n4. **Document the historical advice** — quietly. Write a short internal note for each venture (Alaya, Plamedi, Mariam, Sharon, Hope) summarising what was discussed and that no formal engagement existed. This isn't to share with them, it's for your own protection if any of them later disputes what was said. Date-stamp it.\n5. **For Sharon specifically** — the visa pack you built around the SeedLegals-style C4E + LOI is the *one* that most needs a signed paper trail, because the Home Office can and does reject Spousal Visa applications where the \"employer\" appears to be an informal arrangement. A signed Consultancy Agreement + a counter-signed invoice + a PI-insured Ltd is the strongest possible framing.\n6. **Tell them now** — a short, honest message to all five: *\"I've now formalised my advisory work under a UK Ltd with PI cover. Going forward I'll only give written advice under a signed consultancy agreement. Anything I've said to date that you want to rely on, let me know and I'll put it in writing under the new structure.\"* That's how you contain the bleed without admitting fault.\n\n**Bottom line:** the gap is real but recoverable. Retroactively you can't insure it; going forward you can. The clock for \"going forward\" starts the day your Ltd is incorporated — which is why **step 1 is today, not next week.**\n\n---\n\n## 3. SeedLegals pricing & the webhook question\n\n**Cheapest entry point:** the **\"Start Free\"** tier on SeedLegals gets you a registered company (if you want them to incorporate it) and the basic contracts. After that:\n\n- **Access plan: £649/year + VAT** (≈ £779 inc VAT) — this is the day-to-day plan that includes unlimited cap-table shareholders, team agreements, IP assignment, board docs, the pitch page, and the **Data Room at no extra cost**.\n- **Funding plan: £1,199/year + VAT** — adds SEIS/EIS, funding rounds, Boost, account manager. Buy this only when she's actually raising.\n- **Options plan: £2,699/year + VAT** — only needed if she's granting EMI/Unapproved options.\n- **Pay-as-you-go Flex credits** for one-off events: SeedFAST £150, Bootstrap Round £990, Seed Round £1,990, share issue £299.\n\nFor Plamedi's situation (charity/sole-trader, no raise yet, just needs the governance docs), **the cheapest meaningful plan is Access at £649/year + VAT, paid annually** (monthly is more expensive). That's the £30/month number you put in the April 3 paste — but that was monthly; annual works out closer to £54/month. If she really can't stretch to that, the **free** signup lets her generate a couple of basic agreements but doesn't include the Data Room.\n\n**The webhook claim from the April 3 paste is wrong.** I checked — SeedLegals does **not** expose a public webhook or developer API. The `developers.seedlegals.com` subdomain doesn't even resolve. Their Data Room is UI-only: you upload documents manually, share via \"Groups\" with custom permissions. There is no programmatic way for your n8n workflow to push a signed PDF into the SeedLegals data room automatically. The webhook line in that paste was aspirational/architectural — the actual integration you have to build is *not* SeedLegals → n8n. It's the other way: you store the signed PDF + Decision ID in **your own** OCI/Azure immutable vault, and SeedLegals just becomes the UI layer where Plamedi or an auditor manually uploads the same file.\n\nSo the \"SeedLegals Data Room webhook\" in your April 3 architecture needs to be replaced with: **OCI Object Storage (WORM lock) or Azure Blob (version-level immutability)** as the system-of-record, and SeedLegals as a parallel human-facing copy. Both exist; you don't lose anything by skipping the SeedLegals webhook — you just don't get the false automation.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Cheaper alternatives + Stiwdio access balancing\n\n**Cheaper than SeedLegals, tier by tier:**\n\n| What you need | Free/cheapest option | Cost |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Standard contract templates** (NDA, PSA, CSA, ToS, DPA, etc.) | **Common Paper** — CC BY 4.0, free, written by a committee of 30+ top tech lawyers (Wilson Sonsini, Cooley, Orrick) | £0 |\n| **One-off consultancy agreement** | Common Paper Professional Services Agreement + their Independent Contractor Agreement + Letter of Intent | £0 |\n| **Company incorporation + first set of standard articles** | **Companies House direct** (£12) + Common Paper Articles | £12 + £0 |\n| **Cap table management** | A clean **Google Sheet** template (YC's standard or the SeedLegals export format) until you're past 10 shareholders | £0 |\n| **EMI scheme + valuations** | **Vestd Self-Serve**: £220/month (£2,200/year) — same FCA-regulated, Companies House-integrated stack SeedLegals uses, often cheaper | £2,200/yr |\n| **Seed-round legal pack** | **Vestd InVestd Raise**: £150/month, no completion fees (SeedLegals charges £1,990 flat) | £1,800/yr |\n| **Data room (standalone)** | **Google Drive** with shared drives + **Dropbox Sign** audit trail — institutional investors accept this for sub-£500k rounds | £0–£20/mo |\n| **R&D tax credits** | **Catax / RIFT / EmpowerRD** — they take 15–30% of the claim but you don't pay upfront | success-fee only |\n| **Free EIS-style academy** | **SeedLegals Academy + their free ebooks + the SEIS/EIS pitch-deck guide** | £0 |\n\n**For Plamedi specifically**, the cheapest credible stack is:\n1. Incorporate AFJ Cardiff Ltd via Companies House (£12)\n2. Use **Common Paper** for the NDA, IP Assignment, Consultancy Agreement, Letter of Intent (£0)\n3. Skip SeedLegals until she's actually raising (or pay the £649/yr Access only when she needs a cap table + Data Room)\n4. Use **Google Drive shared drive** as the data room, with **Dropbox Sign** for the audit certificate — free tier covers her volume\n5. Move to SeedLegals / Vestd only when she's ready to issue shares or file SEIS Advance Assurance\n\nTotal cost: **£12 + £0** vs. **£649+** with SeedLegals. Same legal effect for her current pre-incorporation stage.\n\n**Balancing Stiwdio + SeedLegals access rights:**\n\nStiwdio Cardiff is your physical-access credential (the Salto card, the meeting rooms, the \"institutional\" stamp on grant applications). SeedLegals is a software account (one login per email, role-based). They don't actually overlap — but here's how to keep them clean:\n\n- **One email per venture.** Don't mix `afjcardiff@gmail.com` with your personal login. Make a fresh `plamedi@afjcardiff.com` (Google Workspace, £5/user/month) and use that for the SeedLegals account. Same for Alaya/FirstGens, Sharon/Scrollytelling Wales, Mariam/BFB, Hope's charity.\n- **Two roles on each SeedLegals company:** Plamedi = \"Owner/Admin\" (can sign, can delete, can manage cap table). You = \"Advisor\" role (read + comment + sign assigned docs, but can't move shares or close rounds). That mirrors the Founder/Advisor split the April 3 paste already describes.\n- **Invite via email + a Slack/WhatsApp ping** — don't share login credentials. Each person gets their own auth, SeedLegals logs every action by user.\n- **Stiwdio stays paper:** the physical membership (room access, grant-application supporting letter, newsletter) is identity-based, not account-based. It doesn't \"sync\" to SeedLegals at all. The only thing it does is prove Welsh residency + creative-sector credibility when SeedLegals SEIS/EIS or a grant asks \"where are you based\" — and that's a screenshot, not an integration.\n- **Rotate the SeedLegals Owner role once a year** — if Plamedi ever leaves or hands the company over, you don't want her personal email to still be the only Owner. Make it a board-level role.\n\nSo: Stiwdio = ID badge. SeedLegals = software account with two roles. Common Paper / Companies House = the legal-text backbone (free). Vestd = the cheaper SeedLegals alternative when she scales. None of them talk to each other, and they don't need to — the \"integration\" is you (the architect) keeping the paper trail straight.\n\n---\n\nWant me to draft the actual PI-insured Consultancy Agreement you can send to all five founders this week, plus the Companies House incorporation checklist for your own Ltd? That gets the gap closed fastest.",
