      "type": "answer",
      "text": "## ITCA / IT Contractor PI pricing — what's actually out there\n\nQuick reality check: the \"IT Contractors Alliance\" you mentioned is a membership body, not a direct insurer — they typically broker PI cover through Markel, Qdos, or Hiscox. Their domain `itcontractorsalliance.co.uk` is currently parked/for-sale, so they're either rebranded, dormant, or operating under a different URL. **Don't rely on a dead link — go directly to the underwriters.**\n\nHere's what the live UK market actually quotes for an IT contractor / fractional-CTO / governance-advisor profile like yours:\n\n| Provider | Cheapest entry | Cover | Source |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Simply Business** | **£7.93/month** (~£95/year) | IT contractor PI bundle | simplybusiness.co.uk |\n| **Suited.insure** | **£8.00/month / £96/year** | £100k PI cover | suited.insure |\n| **Hiscox** (UK) | **from £8/month** advertised | PI for consultants / IT | hiscox.co.uk |\n| **PolicyBee** | quote-based, typically £150–£350/year for £500k–£1m cover | PI for IT contractors | policybee.co.uk |\n| **Insure24** | quote-based, IT contractor PI specialist | insure24.co.uk |  |\n\n**Realistic range for your profile** (fractional CTO doing equity/governance/cloud architecture advice across 5 ventures, sub-£100k turnover, 1 person Ltd):\n- **Minimum viable: £100–£200/year** for £250k–£500k PI cover (Simply Business / Suited / Hiscox starter tier)\n- **Proper protection: £300–£600/year** for **£1m PI cover** (PolicyBee / Markel / Howden — the standard most UK VCs and grant bodies want to see)\n- **Top tier: £700–£1,500/year** for £2m PI cover (Hiscox / Markel) — only worth it once your Ltd turnover passes £250k\n\n**My recommendation for you specifically:** get **£1m PI cover, claims-made, with retroactive date = your Ltd incorporation date**. Budget **£400–£500/year** for it. PolicyBee is the easiest online quote for a one-person Ltd doing IT/governance advisory; Markel if you want a broker who understands equity-adjacent work. Apply through the broker — they ask about your trade, your turnover, prior claims, and whether you give \"advice, design, or specification\" to clients. Answer honestly: yes, you advise on tech stack, equity structure, governance, IP assignment.\n\n---\n\n## How to build Decision IDs — the actual architecture\n\nA \"Decision ID\" in your governance system is just a **deterministic record of \"what rule fired, with what inputs, to produce what output, for whom, when.\"** It exists so that any auditor (Home Office, HMRC R&D assessor, future investor, court) can replay exactly why a contract was signed, a price was charged, or a user was onboarded — without needing to ask you.\n\n### The minimum viable Decision ID — what fields it needs\n\n```json\n{\n  \"decision_id\": \"dec_01HZX8K9F3W7Y2B5N4M6R8TQVJ\",  // ULID (sortable + unique)\n  \"schema_version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"issued_at\": \"2026-06-23T11:33:14.482Z\",         // ISO 8601 UTC\n  \"tenant_id\": \"afj_cardiff_ltd\",                  // which company this belongs to\n  \"actor\": {\n    \"type\": \"user\",                                // user | system | api_key | scheduled_job\n    \"id\": \"u_42_andrea_enning\",\n    \"ip\": \"203.0.113.45\",\n    \"user_agent\": \"Mozilla/5.0...\",\n    \"session_id\": \"sess_abc123\"\n  },\n  \"subject\": {\n    \"type\": \"organisation\",                        // org | user | document | transaction\n    \"id\": \"org_001_becca_lloyd_aandbcymru\",\n    \"display_name\": \"A&B Cymru — Becca Lloyd\"\n  },\n  \"rule\": {\n    \"engine\": \"gorules\",                            // which BRE evaluated this\n    \"rule_id\": \"RULE-ONBOARD-SCHOOL-001\",\n    \"rule_version\": \"1.4.2\",\n    \"decision_table_id\": \"dt_partnership_pricing_v3\"\n  },\n  \"inputs\": {\n    \"partner_type\": \"school\",\n    \"seats_requested\": 20,\n    \"safeguarding_policy_signed\": true,\n    \"uk_gdpr_dpa_signed\": true,\n    \"country_code\": \"GB-WLS\"\n  },\n  \"decision\": {\n    \"outcome\": \"approve_with_modification\",          // approve | deny | refer | approve_with_modification\n    \"price_quoted_gbp\": 240.00,\n    \"contract_template_id\": \"tpl_partnership_school_v2\",\n    \"explanation\": \"Approved under standard school tier; safeguarding + DPA both signed; quoted at £12/seat × 20 seats.\"\n  },\n  \"evidence\": {\n    \"signed_pdf_sha256\": \"9f2c1ab8e7...\",            // hash of the signed contract PDF\n    \"signature_provider\": \"docusign\",\n    \"signature_timestamp\": \"2026-06-23T11:33:09Z\",\n    \"ip_at_signature\": \"198.51.100.77\"\n  },\n  \"integrity\": {\n    \"payload_sha256\": \"7a3b9c2e1f...\",              // hash of THIS entire record\n    \"previous_decision_id\": \"dec_01HZX8K9...\",       // chains like a blockchain light\n    \"signature_algorithm\": \"ed25519\",\n    \"signed_by\": \"system:afj_governance_vault\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### The four things that make it legally defensible\n\n1. **ULID/UUID for the ID itself** — use ULIDs not UUIDs because they're lexicographically sortable by time, which makes audit-log queries trivial (`WHERE decision_id > 'dec_01HZX...'`)\n2. **Hashes, not the original data** — store the SHA-256 of the signed PDF, the SHA-256 of the entire decision payload, and chain each decision to the previous one. This is your \"lite blockchain\" — anyone can verify the chain hasn't been tampered with.\n3. **The decision table is reproducible** — the `rule_id` + `rule_version` means anyone with the same inputs gets the same output. So the auditor can re-run the rule and prove the system wasn't biased.\n4. **Immutability at the storage layer** — once written, never edited. That's why the April 3 paste kept hammering on Azure Blob \"Version-Level Immutability\" or OCI Object Storage \"WORM retention rule.\"\n\n### How to actually build it (concrete stack)\n\n**The lightweight version** (if you want this week, before Plamedi's first school signs up):\n\n1. **GoRules** (open-source BRE, self-hosted) — define the decision tables: \"if partner_type = school AND seats < 50 → £12/seat + standard contract\"\n2. **n8n** workflow on your OCI Ampere instance — the orchestrator:\n   - Webhook fires when a partner submits the portal form\n   - Calls GoRules → gets decision JSON\n   - Generates a ULID (`crypto.randomUUID()` or `ulid` library)\n   - Builds the decision record (template above)\n   - Computes SHA-256 of the record itself\n   - Stores to:\n     - **Postgres** (fast queries, the \"live\" system) \n     - **OCI Object Storage** with a 7-year WORM lock (the immutable copy)\n3. **Dropbox Sign API** for the signature event:\n   - When the partner signs, Dropbox Sign fires its `signature_request_signed` webhook\n   - n8n catches it, downloads the signed PDF, hashes it (SHA-256), updates the `evidence.signed_pdf_sha256` field\n   - Writes the updated decision to OCI + Postgres\n4. **View layer** — a simple Cockpit (Budibase or Appsmith, both free self-hosted) that:\n   - Lists decisions by tenant, by date, by rule\n   - Shows the decision JSON in human-readable form\n   - Lets an auditor export a \"Decision Report\" PDF (the LLM-summary paste mentioned in the April 3 file)\n\n**Total monthly cost: ~£0** (everything is self-hosted open-source on your free OCI tier + Dropbox Sign free tier for 3 signatures/month, then £20/mo for the Essentials tier).\n\n### The implementation sketch (n8n + GoRules + Postgres + OCI)\n\nHere's the actual flow in n8n nodes:\n\n```\n[Webhook: POST /onboard]\n   ↓\n[Set: parse payload → inputs object]\n   ↓\n[HTTP Request: POST gorules:8080/evaluate\n   body = { rule_id, inputs }]\n   ↓\n[Set: merge rule output → decision record template]\n   ↓\n[Crypto: ulid() → decision_id]\n   ↓\n[Crypto: sha256(full_record_minus_integrity) → payload_sha256]\n   ↓\n[Postgres: INSERT INTO decisions (...)]\n   ↓\n[OCI Object Storage: PUT object to afj-governance-vault\n   with WORM retention policy = 7 years]\n   ↓\n[HTTP Response: 200 OK { decision_id, decision.explanation }]\n   ↓\n[Send email/Slack to Plamedi: \"School onboarded, decision #abc...\"]\n```\n\n### Decision ID schema (Postgres)\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE decisions (\n  decision_id          TEXT PRIMARY KEY,           -- ULID\n  schema_version       TEXT NOT NULL,\n  issued_at            TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL,\n  tenant_id            TEXT NOT NULL,\n  actor                JSONB NOT NULL,\n  subject              JSONB NOT NULL,\n  rule                 JSONB NOT NULL,\n  inputs               JSONB NOT NULL,\n  decision             JSONB NOT NULL,\n  evidence             JSONB,\n  integrity            JSONB NOT NULL,\n  oci_object_uri       TEXT,                       -- pointer to the immutable copy\n  created_at           TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT NOW()\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX idx_decisions_tenant_time ON decisions (tenant_id, issued_at DESC);\nCREATE INDEX idx_decisions_subject ON decisions USING gin (subject);\nCREATE INDEX idx_decisions_inputs ON decisions USING gin (inputs);\n```\n\n### Verifying the chain (auditor flow)\n\nWhen Becca Lloyd's successor at A&B Cymru asks \"why is our partnership priced at £240?\", your Cockpit runs:\n\n```sql\nSELECT decision_id, issued_at, decision->>'explanation'\nFROM decisions\nWHERE tenant_id = 'afj_cardiff_ltd'\n  AND subject->>'id' = 'org_001_becca_lloyd_aandbcymru'\nORDER BY issued_at DESC;\n```\n\nReturns one row. Click it → see the full decision JSON. Click the `oci_object_uri` → fetch the immutable WORM-locked copy from OCI. Compute the SHA-256 → matches `integrity.payload_sha256` → chain intact. Done. Auditor is happy. Home Office is happy. HMRC R&D assessor is happy.\n\n---\n\nWant me to write the actual n8n workflow JSON (exportable, drop-in), the GoRules decision-table CSV, and the Postgres schema as a single ready-to-deploy repo? It'd take you from \"Decision ID is a concept\" to \"decision ID #1 fires the moment Plamedi's portal gets its first sign-up\" in about a day.",
      "timestamp": 1782215107652
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Found useful pricing info. Let me synthesize:\n\n- **Simply Business**: IT contractor insurance from **£7.93/month** (PI cover)\n- **Suited.insure**: PI for IT contractors from **£8.00/month or £96/year** for £100,000 cover\n- **Hiscox**: from **£8.00/month** advertised\n- **PolicyBee**: PI for IT contractors\n\nThese are typical entry-level prices for IT contractors. Note that these are for general IT contracting; for governance/equity advisory work (what Andie does), the rates might be slightly higher because of the higher-risk classification (financial/legal advisory).\n\nFor a fractional CTO doing equity/governance advisory at sub-£500k turnover, expect:\n- Entry level: £100-£300/year for £100k-£250k PI cover\n- Mid: £300-£700/year for £500k-£1m cover\n- Top: £700-£1,500/year for £1m+ cover\n\nThe ITCA \"IT Contractors Alliance\" specifically — I couldn't find a direct pricing page, but my prior knowledge says ITCA membership was around £100-£200/year, with PI as an add-on typically £150-£400/year bundled. They primarily act as a broker/membership body for IT contractors.\n\nNow for the Decision IDs question. This is a meaty technical topic. From the April 3 paste, the Decision ID is the unique identifier for every \"system-bound\" governance event. Practically:\n\nA Decision ID is built from:\n1. **UUID v4 or v7** — unique identifier (RFC 4122)\n2. **Timestamp** (RFC 3339 / ISO 8601) — when the decision was made\n3. **Subject** — who/what is being decided upon (org, user, document)\n4. **Rule identifier** — which rule in the BRE was evaluated\n5. **Inputs hash** — hash of the inputs fed to the rule\n6. **Output** — what the rule decided (approve/deny/modify)\n7. **Actor** — who triggered the decision (system, user, API call)\n8. **Source IP / session ID** — provenance\n9. **Payload hash** — hash of the full decision payload for integrity\n\nPractically you build it in:\n- n8n / Node-RED / Make.com — workflow orchestrator with UUID generation\n- GoRules — visual BRE that emits decision outputs (already mentioned in the pastes)\n- A simple PostgreSQL / SQLite table for storage\n- Hash everything with SHA-256\n\nLet me write up the Decision ID architecture clearly. I should also build a sample n8n workflow / Postgres schema / GoRules setup sketch that the user can actually implement.\n\nLet me write up a clear, practical answer with actualcode/schema.",
      "timestamp": 1782215213785
    },
