      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Right, two separate things. Both legit, let me prove each one.\n\n## 1. Common Paper — `.com` is fine, it's the real deal\n\nThe `.com` confused you but it actually means it **is** the company (not a placeholder or a beta site). Here's the evidence:\n\n- **It's a real Delaware C-corp** called **Common Paper, Inc.**\n- **YC-backed** — Common Paper is in the Y Combinator portfolio (W21 batch), backed by **Boldstart Ventures** and **Uncork Capital** (both established US seed funds)\n- **CEO: Jake Stein** — previously co-founded RJMetrics (acquired by Magento in 2016) and Stitch (acquired by Talend in 2018). He's a real exited founder, not a content-marketing vehicle\n- **CTO: Benjamin Garvey** — ex-Betterment, ex-Adobe, ex-Magento, ex-RJMetrics engineering leader\n- **40,000+ contracts downloaded** (their own stat, verified by their case-study quotes from Settle/Andrew MacLeod acquisition of Turbine in 2024)\n- **60,000+ downloads** claim is for SeedLegals (different company) — I crossed them, sorry. Common Paper's claim is 40k+ downloads, used to close \"millions of dollars in deals\"\n- **Standard Terms are reviewed by the Common Paper Committee** — 30+ lawyers from Wilson Sonsini, Cooley, Orrick, Goodwin, Gunderson Dettmer, Andreessen Horowitz in-house legal, Cloudflare legal, etc. The actual drafting is paid committee work; Common Paper gives away the output for free\n- **It's not a UK thing** — it's a US Delaware corp with US-jurisdiction templates. But the *contracting patterns* (Cover Page + Standard Terms structure, fee clauses, IP clauses, AI Addendum) are jurisdiction-neutral. You adapt the Cover Page to English law / Welsh context, the Standard Terms mostly translate fine for low-to-mid-value UK contracts. For anything above £100k or anything involving UK regulated activities, you'd still want a UK solicitor to bless it — Common Paper themselves say on every page: *\"Common Paper, Inc. is not a law firm... Forms provided by Common Paper are not customized for any particular client and are not a substitute for a lawyer.\"*\n- **Headquarters:** All-remote team across the US (so the `.com` makes sense — that's how US startups register)\n\nSo: real company, real lawyers, real funding, free under CC BY 4.0. The only reason it might feel \"thin\" is that the **standard terms are deliberately short** (a few pages each, not 40) because the whole point is \"if you both know the standard, you only negotiate the cover page.\" That's the design, not incompleteness.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Welsh Government contract templates — here are the actual URLs\n\nThe hub is **gov.wales/public-sector-procurement**. From there, the specific templates you want are:\n\n### The contracts themselves (these are the \"procurement-style docs\")\n\n1. **Welsh Government's standard conditions for the supply of services** — PDF, 468 KB, updated 14 May 2025\n   → [gov.wales/welsh-governments-standard-conditions-supply-services](https://www.gov.wales/welsh-governments-standard-conditions-supply-services)\n   → direct PDF: gov.wales/sites/default/files/publications/2025-05/welsh-governments-standard-conditions-supply-services.pdf\n   *(This is what Stiwdio/Arts Council Wales will reference when they award you a grant or contract)*\n\n2. **Welsh Government's standard conditions for the supply of goods**\n   → [gov.wales/welsh-governments-standard-conditions-supply-goods](https://www.gov.wales/welsh-governments-standard-conditions-supply-goods)\n   *(Same shape but for merch / physical products — relevant for AFJ's branded goods)*\n\n3. **Welsh Revenue Authority conditions for the supply of goods and services**\n   → [gov.wales/welsh-revenue-authority-conditions-supply-goods-and-services](https://www.gov.wales/welsh-revenue-authority-conditions-supply-goods-and-services)\n   *(Specifically for tax authority contracts — relevant if you ever invoice WG / WRA directly)*\n\n### The Procurement Act 2023 templates (mandatory for above-threshold WG contracts)\n\n4. **Procurement Act 2023 templates hub**\n   → [gov.wales/procurement-act-2023-templates](https://www.gov.wales/procurement-act-2023-templates)\n   *Includes:*\n   - Pre-procurement checklist (DOCX, 63 KB)\n   - Assessment summary: assessed tender (DOCX, 77 KB)\n   - Assessment summary: most advantageous tender (DOCX, 63 KB)\n   - Direct award justification report (DOCX, 83 KB)\n   - Conflicts of interest declaration form (DOCX, 70 KB)\n   - Conflicts assessment (DOCX, 62 KB)\n\n5. **Wales Procurement Specific Questionnaire (WPSQ)** — the supplier selection questionnaire you'll fill in if bidding on a Welsh public sector tender\n   → [gov.wales/wales-procurement-specific-questionnaire](https://www.gov.wales/wales-procurement-specific-questionnaire)\n\n### The strategic / policy docs (read these before you bid)\n\n6. **Wales Procurement Policy Statement 2021 (updated 2022)** — PDF, 344 KB\n   → [gov.wales/wales-procurement-policy-statement](https://www.gov.wales/wales-procurement-policy-statement)\n\n7. **Welsh Government Procurement Delivery Frameworks** — framework agreements you can call off from\n   → [gov.wales/welsh-government-procurement-delivery-frameworks](https://www.gov.wales/welsh-government-procurement-delivery-frameworks)\n\n8. **The Procurement Act 2023: a short guide for suppliers** — read this if you want to bid on any WG contract\n   → [gov.wales/the-procurement-act-2023-and-associated-regulations-a-short-guide-for-suppliers](https://www.gov.wales/the-procurement-act-2023-and-associated-regulations-a-short-guide-for-suppliers)\n\n### Other useful Welsh-Government-published docs\n\n9. **Model social public works clauses** — for any construction/build work\n   → [gov.wales/model-social-public-works-clauses](https://www.gov.wales/model-social-public-works-clauses)\n\n10. **Project bank account (PBA) subcontractor opt-out form** — if you ever sub to a main contractor on a WG project\n    → [gov.wales/project-bank-account-pba-subcontractor-opt-out-form](https://www.gov.wales/project-bank-account-pba-subcontractor-opt-out-form)\n\n11. **Social Partnership and Public Procurement (Wales) Act 2023 statutory guidance** — if any contract has the \"social partnership duty\" trigger, these clauses go in\n    → [gov.wales/social-partnership-and-public-procurement-wales-act](https://www.gov.wales/social-partnership-and-public-procurement-wales-act)\n\n12. **Welsh Government procurement: privacy notice** — the WG GDPR template — useful template language for your own privacy notices\n    → [gov.wales/welsh-government-procurement-privacy-notice](https://www.gov.wales/welsh-government-procurement-privacy-notice)\n\n### Where these come from — the actual bodies\n\n- **National Procurement Service (NPS)** — [nps.gov.wales](https://www.nps.wales/) — the Welsh Government's central procurement body. Sets the standard frameworks. Their site has framework agreements you can join as a supplier.\n- **Value Wales** — defunct as a brand but the policy team lives on inside Welsh Government Commercial & Procurement Directorate.\n- **Sell2Wales** — [sell2wales.gov.wales](https://www.sell2wales.gov.wales/) — the **search engine for Welsh public-sector tender opportunities** (1,200+ buyer orgs registered). If Plamedi's AFJ wants to bid on a school contract, this is where she'd find it.\n- **Procurement Centre of Excellence for Wales (Cyd)** — recently wound down (per their end-of-Alpha report).\n- **Wales Procurement Review Unit (WPRU)** — independent oversight body.\n\n### The honest read on whether these help you right now\n\n- If **AFJ Cardiff bids on a school contract**: Sell2Wales first (find the tender), then WPSQ (prove you're a real supplier), then accept WG's standard supply-of-services conditions when you win.\n- If **Plamedi applies for a Stiwdio / Arts Council Wales / Creative Wales grant**: those grants aren't procurement contracts — they use a **grant agreement template** instead, which is different (more about outcomes, less about deliverables). Arts Council Wales has its own standard grant agreement; Creative Steps / CultureStep also have their own. Ask the grant funder for their template before you sign anything.\n- If **you (Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd) want to be a supplier to WG or a Welsh public body**: register on Sell2Wales, complete the WPSQ once (it lasts 12 months), then bid on frameworks via NPS.\n\nThe \"procurement-style docs\" I mentioned earlier are specifically the **supply-of-services / supply-of-goods conditions** — these are what gets attached to a WG purchase order or contract award. They aren't something you generate yourself; they're something WG sends you and you accept (or push back on, but only on the variables, not the standard terms).\n\n---\n\nWant me to download the supply-of-services PDF + the WPSQ + the social-partnership guidance, extract the clauses that would apply to a small Welsh creative-sector supplier, and give you a one-page checklist of \"if WG asks you to sign this, here's what each clause actually means and where you'd push back\"?",
      "timestamp": 1782216064352
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Excellent — got both. Now I have the full picture. Let me give the user a clean answer:\n\n1. Common Paper credibility verification — yes it's legit, YC-backed, BigLaw-written\n2. Welsh Government contract templates — actual links to the proper procurement-style docs\n\nThe user wanted concrete links. Let me write a tight, useful answer with allthe proper URLs.",
