    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Right, here's Plamedi's full pack — three documents, ready to drop in names and sign.\n\n---\n\n## Document 1: Mutual NDA\n\n**Between:** Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd (you) ↔ AFJ Cardiff Ltd (her)\n\n```\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n                  MUTUAL NON-DISCLOSURE AGREEMENT\n                            Cover Page\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\nThis Mutual Non-Disclosure Agreement consists of:\n  (1) this Cover Page, and\n  (2) the Common Paper Mutual NDA Standard Terms Version 1.0\n      posted at commonpaper.com/standards/mutual-nda/1.0\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nPARTIES\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nPARTY 1 (Provider):  Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd\n                     Company No. [to be assigned by Companies House]\n                     Registered office: [your Welsh address]\n                     Director: Andrea Enning (known as \"Andie\")\n\nPARTY 2 (Customer):  AFJ Cardiff Ltd\n                     Company No. [to be assigned by Companies House]\n                     Registered office: [Plamedi's Welsh address]\n                     Director: Plamedi [surname TBC]\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nCOVER PAGE VARIABLES\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nPURPOSE\n  Why we're sharing confidential information:\n  \"Evaluating and entering into a long-term consultancy arrangement,\n   including the design, build, hosting and ongoing operation of the\n   AFJ Cardiff digital platform, and exploring partnership opportunities\n   (including with Stiwdio Newport, Arts Council Wales, A&B Cymru and\n   similar Welsh cultural-sector organisations).\"\n\nEFFECTIVE DATE\n  [X] Date of last signature on this Cover Page\n\nMNDA TERM (how long we can share secrets)\n  [X] Expires 2 years from the Effective Date\n\nTERM OF CONFIDENTIALITY (how long the secrets stay protected)\n  [X] 3 years from the date of last disclosure,\n      but trade secrets stay protected until they stop being trade\n      secrets under English law\n\nGOVERNING LAW\n  The laws of England and Wales\n\nJURISDICTION\n  The courts of England and Wales\n\nCHANGES TO STANDARD TERMS\n  [Include this from Common Paper's Language Library:]\n  \"Confidential Information includes any such information disclosed\n   or made available before or after the Effective Date.\"\n\n  Reason: Plamedi has already shared curriculum content, brand\n  materials, partnership emails (A&B Cymru / Stiwdio) and student\n  data with Andie verbally and via Google Drive before any contract\n  exists. This clause makes sure all of that back-history is covered.\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nSIGNATURES\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nPARTY 1 — Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd\n  Signature: __________________________\n  Print Name: Andrea Enning\n  Title: Director\n  Notice Address: [your business email]\n  Date: __________________________\n\nPARTY 2 — AFJ Cardiff Ltd\n  Signature: __________________________\n  Print Name: Plamedi [surname]\n  Title: Director\n  Notice Address: [her business email]\n  Date: __________________________\n```\n\n**Why these choices:**\n- **Purpose is broad** (not just \"build a website\") because you'll be discussing curriculum, IP, partnerships, grant applications, student data, equity, hiring — all of which generate confidential info.\n- **2-year MNDA Term, 3-year confidentiality tail** is the Common Paper default-ish but I gave it more time because charities often have long grant cycles (UK Arts Council / Welsh Government can take 18+ months from first chat to award).\n- **Pre-effective-date clause** is the bit the April 3 paste overlooked — without it, the back-history of what you've already shared is technically unprotected.\n\n---\n\n## Document 2: Consultancy Agreement + SLA\n\n**This is the big one.** Andie = Provider. AFJ Cardiff Ltd = Customer.\n\n```\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n           PROFESSIONAL SERVICES AGREEMENT (Consultancy)\n                            Cover Page\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\nThis SOW incorporates the Common Paper Professional Services Agreement\nStandard Terms Version 1.1 (posted at\ncommonpaper.com/standards/professional-services-agreement/1.1)\ntogether with the Key Terms set out below.\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nSOW VARIABLES — THE \"WHAT ARE WE DOING\" HALF\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nSOW NUMBER\n  AFJ-CONS-001 (first engagement; number future SOWs sequentially\n                 e.g. AFJ-CONS-002, AFJ-CONS-003, etc.)\n\nPROVIDER\n  Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd\n  Company No. [TBC] · Director: Andrea Enning (\"Andie\")\n\nCUSTOMER\n  AFJ Cardiff Ltd\n  Company No. [TBC] · Director: Plamedi [surname]\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nSERVICES\n  Andie will act as the Customer's fractional Chief Technology\n  Officer and Platform Architect. The Services include:\n\n  (a) Cloud architecture, infrastructure design and ongoing\n      technical operation of the Customer's digital platform\n      (the \"AFJ Portal\") hosted on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure\n      Always-Free tier (or equivalent free-tier equivalent),\n      secured behind Cloudflare Zero Trust Tunnels and fronted\n      by Authentik single sign-on.\n\n  (b) Automation design and integration using n8n, GoRules and\n      equivalent open-source tools, including a decision-ID\n      framework that produces an auditable, immutable record of\n      every system-bound governance event (contract signing,\n      partner onboarding, pricing decisions, safeguarding\n      confirmations).\n\n  (c) Governance, security and data-protection advice aligned to\n      UK GDPR, the Data Protection Act 2018 and the Welsh\n      Government's Social Partnership and Public Procurement\n      (Wales) Act 2023 statutory guidance, where relevant.\n\n  (d) Liaison with the Customer's grant-funder compliance\n      requirements, including Arts Council Wales, Creative Steps,\n      CultureStep, Stiwdio Newport and similar Welsh\n      cultural-sector programmes.\n\n  (e) Ad-hoc strategic advice on technology vendor selection,\n      partnership structuring, IP ownership and R&D tax-credit\n      claims (the Customer remains responsible for its own\n      filings).\n\n  The Services do NOT include: legal advice (Andie is not a\n  solicitor), regulated financial advice, or any activity that\n  requires a regulated professional qualification.\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nDELIVERABLES\n  The deliverables include:\n   - the live, operational AFJ Portal\n   - the underlying Infrastructure-as-Code repository (OCI\n     Terraform / Docker Compose)\n   - the n8n workflow definitions\n   - the GoRules decision tables\n   - the Authentik SSO configuration\n   - the \"Digital Data Room\" (Azure Blob with version-level\n     immutability, or OCI Object Storage with WORM retention)\n   - architecture decision records (\"ADRs\") and design notes\n\n  [X] In addition to completed deliverables, \"Deliverables\"\n      includes in-progress but not complete drafts, components\n      and associated intellectual property (this stops AFJ Cardiff\n      Ltd from owning only \"finished\" bits and leaving you with\n      orphaned work-in-progress).\n\n  [X] Customer owns Deliverables upon payment of the associated\n      Fees (Andie retains ownership until AFJ Cardiff Ltd has\n      paid — standard provider-favourable position; matches the\n      \"Liability Decoupling\" framing in the April 3 paste).\n\nTIME OF ASSIGNMENT\n  [X] Customer owns Deliverables upon payment of associated Fees.\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nTHIRD-PARTY MATERIALS\n  [X] Third-Party Materials will be incorporated into Deliverables.\n\n  The Provider will procure Third-Party Materials, including but\n  not limited to:\n   - Open-source software (Authentik, n8n, GoRules, Frappe/ERPNext\n     or Odoo Community, SeaweedFS, Outline, Appsmith, Budibase,\n     Penpot) under their respective open-source licences\n   - Oracle Cloud Always-Free tier infrastructure\n   - Cloudflare free-tier services\n   - Dropbox Sign / DocuSeal free-tier signatures\n   - Any paid software or services will be pre-approved in writing\n     by the Customer before purchase.\n\n  [X] Provider will procure Third-Party Materials.\n  [ ] Customer will procure Third-Party Materials.\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nFEES\n  The Customer will pay the Provider:\n\n   (a) A monthly retainer of £0 (zero) for the first twelve (12)\n       months from the SOW Date. This is in recognition of the\n       Customer's pre-incorporation status, limited cash flow and\n       the strategic / equity-adjacent nature of the engagement.\n\n   (b) From month 13 onwards, a monthly retainer of £[TBD — recommend\n       £1,500–£2,500/month, market rate for a fractional CTO with\n       cloud architecture + governance specialism in the Welsh\n       third sector], reviewable annually.\n\n   (c) Reimbursement of pre-approved out-of-pocket expenses\n       (cloud services that exceed the free tier, software\n       licences, travel to Stiwdio Newport or to Customer's\n       premises).\n\n   (d) A success fee equal to 10% of any grant funding received\n       by the Customer where the Provider's written work product\n       (architecture, dashboards, ADR pack, audit reports) was\n       a material input to the application. This clause exists\n       so the Customer can preserve cash while still recognising\n       the Provider's contribution to grant-funded outcomes.\n\n  [X] Travel and expenses: pre-approved in writing (email is\n      sufficient) by the Customer's Director before being incurred.\n\nPAYMENT PERIOD\n  30 days from the Customer's receipt of invoice\n\nINVOICE PERIOD\n  Monthly, sent on the last business day of each month\n  (or quarterly, by mutual agreement)\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nSOW DATE\n  [X] Date of last signature on this Cover Page\n\nSOW TERM\n  [X] 12 months from the SOW Date, automatically renewing for\n      successive 12-month periods unless either party gives\n      60 days' written notice before the end of the current\n      term.\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nCUSTOMER OBLIGATIONS\n  The Customer will:\n   (a) provide timely access to curriculum content, brand\n       materials, student data and any other information needed\n       to deliver the Services\n   (b) respond to Provider requests for approval within 5 business\n       days; if no response, the Provider may treat silence as\n       approval and notify the Customer in writing\n   (c) nominate a single point of contact (the Director) for\n       day-to-day decisions\n   (d) maintain its own UK GDPR / DPA compliance and obtain all\n       necessary parental / guardian consents for processing\n       student personal data\n   (e) maintain Public Liability insurance of at least £1 million\n       covering in-person activities (dance classes, performances)\n   (f) pay the Provider's invoices within the Payment Period\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nKEY TERMS — THE \"WHAT IF IT GOES WRONG\" HALF\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nEFFECTIVE DATE\n  [X] Date of last signature on this Cover Page\n\nGOVERNING LAW\n  The laws of England and Wales\n\nCHOSEN COURTS\n  The courts of England and Wales\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nCOVERED CLAIMS\n\n[X] Provider Covered Claims:\n    (a) the Deliverables (excluding Customer Materials and\n        Customer-procured Third-Party Materials), when used by\n        the Customer per the terms of this SOW, do not infringe\n        anyone else's intellectual property or other proprietary\n        rights\n    (b) Provider's employees or Subcontractors are not deemed\n        to be Customer's employees because of Provider's actions\n    (c) anything arising from Provider's gross negligence, fraud\n        or wilful misconduct\n\n[X] Customer Covered Claims:\n    (a) Customer Materials or Customer-procured Third-Party\n        Materials, when used by Provider per this SOW, do not\n        infringe anyone else's intellectual property\n    (b) anything arising from Customer's gross negligence, fraud\n        or wilful misconduct\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nLIABILITY CAPS\n\nGENERAL CAP AMOUNT\n  [X] 1× the fees paid or payable by Customer to Provider in the\n      12-month period immediately before the claim.\n\n  Practical effect: while fees are £0 (first year), the cap is £0.\n  From year 2 onward, the cap is one month's retainer (e.g. £2,000).\n  This is intentionally tight — the Provider carries minimal\n  financial exposure while the engagement is grant-funded.\n\nINCREASED CLAIMS (higher cap)\n  [X] An Indemnifying Party's indemnification obligations for its\n      Covered Claims\n  [X] Breach of Section 11 (Confidentiality) excluding breach of\n      Section 3 (Privacy & Security)\n  [X] Breach of Section 3 (Privacy & Security) resulting from gross\n      negligence or wilful misconduct\n\nINCREASED CAP AMOUNT\n  [X] The greater of £10,000 or 1× fees paid in the prior 12 months\n\nUNLIMITED CLAIMS (no cap at all)\n  [X] Claims resulting from a party's gross negligence, fraud or\n      wilful misconduct\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nINSURANCE MINIMUMS\n\n[X] For the Provider:\n    [X] Professional Indemnity (Errors & Omissions) — minimum\n        £1,000,000 each occurrence, £1,000,000 aggregate\n    [X] Cyber liability — minimum £500,000 each occurrence,\n        £500,000 aggregate\n    [X] Public Liability — minimum £1,000,000 each occurrence\n    (these three together cost roughly £400–£600/year from\n     Hiscox / PolicyBee / Markel; recommended broker below)\n\n[X] For the Customer:\n    [X] Public Liability — minimum £1,000,000 each occurrence\n        (covers in-person dance classes, school workshops, etc.)\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nATTACHMENTS AND SUPPLEMENTS\n\n[X] DPA: The parties have entered into a Data Processing Agreement\n    on [date], based on the Common Paper DPA Standard Terms Version\n    [X.X], which controls each party's rights and obligations\n    regarding Personal Data.\n\n[X] Customer Policies: AFJ Cardiff's safeguarding policy, equal\n    opportunities policy and data protection policy will be made\n    available to the Provider on request.\n\n[X] Security Policy: the Provider will maintain annually updated\n    evidence of:\n    [X] ISO 27001 alignment (or equivalent: Cyber Essentials Plus)\n    [X] Penetration testing annually by an independent CREST-accredited\n        tester\n    [X] PCI: not applicable (no card data handled)\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nPUBLICITY RIGHTS (modifying Section 12.7 of Standard Terms)\n  [X] Provider may identify Customer and use Customer's name and\n      logo on Provider's website and in marketing materials to\n      identify Customer as a client.\n  [X] Provider may identify Customer as a client in non-public\n      settings (with prospective clients, advisors, regulators,\n      grant funders).\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nOTHER CHANGES TO STANDARD TERMS\n\n  (1) SURVIVAL EXTENSION — replace the last sentence of Section\n      5.4(a) (Survival) with:\n      \"Notwithstanding any expiration or termination, the Provider's\n       confidentiality obligations under Section 11 and the IP\n       assignment under Section 2.1 survive for seven (7) years\n       from the date of expiration or termination.\"\n      Reason: typical 7-year retention period for Welsh public-\n      sector audit trail alignment (Social Partnership and Public\n      Procurement (Wales) Act 2023 contracts register).\n\n  (2) NO AUTOMATIC IP TRANSFER ON TERMINATION — add a new\n      Section 2.7:\n      \"On termination of this Agreement or any SOW for any reason\n       other than Customer's material breach cured under Section\n       5.2(a)(i), Provider grants Customer a perpetual, irrevocable,\n       worldwide, royalty-free licence to use, copy, modify and\n       distribute the Deliverables (excluding Provider's\n       Pre-Existing Materials) for the Customer's ongoing\n       business operations. Title in the Deliverables transfers\n       to Customer upon full payment of all accrued and future\n       Fees owed to Provider as at the termination date.\"\n      Reason: stops AFJ Cardiff Ltd from losing access to its\n      own platform if it can no longer afford fees.\n\n  (3) WELSH LANGUAGE CLAUSE — add a new Section 12.16:\n      \"The Parties acknowledge that the Welsh Language (Wales)\n       Measure 2011 applies to the Customer's public-facing\n       activities. Where any Deliverable, user interface, public\n       communication or policy document is required by the\n       Customer to be available in Welsh, the Provider will\n       source Welsh-language copy from the Customer at no\n       additional cost and integrate it into the Deliverable.\n       The Provider is not responsible for translation accuracy.\"\n      Reason: protects you from being treated as a translator;\n      keeps Customer responsible for Welsh-language source.\n\n  (4) STUDIO NEWPORT REFERENCE — add to the Notices section:\n      \"Provider's status as a member of Stiwdio Newport is\n       acknowledged. Provider may cite the Customer's\n       engagement as a Stiwdio-supported project in any Stiwdio\n       reporting, marketing or funder engagement.\"\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nSIGNATURES\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nPROVIDER — Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd\n  Signature: __________________________\n  Print Name: Andrea Enning\n  Title: Director\n  Notice Address: [your business email]\n  Date: __________________________\n\nCUSTOMER — AFJ Cardiff Ltd\n  Signature: __________________________\n  Print Name: Plamedi [surname]\n  Title: Director\n  Notice Address: [her business email]\n  Date: __________________________\n```\n\n---\n\n## Document 3: IP Assignment Addendum\n\nThis is the bit that makes the April 3 paste's \"AFJ Cardiff Ltd owns everything you build\" actually stick. It's added as a separate one-page addendum to the PSA so it's legally clean.\n\n```\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n           IP ASSIGNMENT AND MORAL RIGHTS WAIVER\n              (Addendum to SOW AFJ-CONS-001)\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\nBetween:\n  PROVIDER:  Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd\n  CUSTOMER:  AFJ Cardiff Ltd\n\nEFFECTIVE DATE: [same as PSA Cover Page]\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n1. ASSIGNMENT\n\n   1.1  The Provider hereby assigns to the Customer absolutely\n        and with full title guarantee all of the Provider's\n        existing and future right, title and interest (including\n        all intellectual property rights) in and to:\n\n        (a) the Deliverables as defined in SOW AFJ-CONS-001,\n            except for the Provider's Pre-Existing Materials\n            and Third-Party Materials procured by the Provider\n            under the open-source licences listed in the\n            SOW Cover Page;\n\n        (b) all design documents, architecture decision records\n            (\"ADRs\"), data-flow diagrams, configuration files,\n            Terraform / Docker Compose scripts, GoRules decision\n            tables, n8n workflow JSON exports, Authentik\n            configuration files, and other technical artefacts\n            created by the Provider specifically for the\n            Customer's platform;\n\n        (c) all website copy, UI text, user-journey\n            documentation, training materials, governance\n            playbooks and operating procedures created by the\n            Provider specifically for the Customer.\n\n   1.2  The assignment in clause 1.1 takes effect:\n\n        (a) immediately, in respect of all works created on or\n            after the Effective Date of this Addendum; and\n\n        (b) retrospectively, in respect of all works created by\n            the Provider for or on behalf of the Customer at\n            any time in the 12 months immediately preceding the\n            Effective Date of this Addendum (the \"Look-Back\n            Period\"). The Look-Back Period is necessary because\n            the Provider has been informally advising the\n            Customer on the AFJ Portal since [date the pastes\n            reference — circa early 2026].\n\n   1.3  The Provider will, at the Customer's reasonable cost,\n        execute such further documents and do such further acts\n        as the Customer may reasonably require to perfect the\n        assignment in clause 1.1.\n\n2. PRE-EXISTING MATERIALS\n\n   2.1  The Provider retains ownership of its Pre-Existing\n        Materials (defined in Section 13 of the PSA Standard\n        Terms).\n\n   2.2  The Provider grants the Customer a non-exclusive,\n        perpetual, irrevocable, worldwide, royalty-free licence\n        to use, copy, modify and distribute the Provider's\n        Pre-Existing Materials to the extent they are\n        incorporated into the Deliverables, solely for the\n        Customer's business operations.\n\n   2.3  The Provider's Pre-Existing Materials include (without\n        limitation):\n        - the Provider's standard n8n node library\n        - the Provider's standard GoRules decision-table\n          templates\n        - the Provider's standard OCI Terraform modules\n        - any open-source components authored by the Provider\n          and released under an OSI-approved licence\n\n3. MORAL RIGHTS WAIVER\n\n   3.1  To the extent permitted by applicable law, the Provider\n        irrevocably and unconditionally waives in favour of the\n        Customer and its successors in title all moral rights\n        (as defined in Chapter IV of Part I of the Copyright,\n        Designs and Patents Act 1988) to which the Provider is\n        or may become entitled in respect of the Deliverables.\n\n   3.2  The Provider agrees not to assert such moral rights\n        against the Customer or any person authorised by the\n        Customer.\n\n4. CONSIDERATION\n\n   4.1  The parties acknowledge that the consideration for this\n        assignment is the mutual obligations set out in SOW\n        AFJ-CONS-001, including the Fees, Customer Obligations\n        and Survival terms set out therein.\n\n5. THIRD-PARTY MATERIALS\n\n   5.1  Nothing in this Addendum assigns or transfers any right\n        in any Third-Party Material. Third-Party Materials\n        incorporated into the Deliverables remain subject to\n        their respective open-source licences (MIT, Apache 2.0,\n        AGPL, LGPL, EUPL or other applicable licence).\n\n6. GOVERNING LAW\n\n   6.1  This Addendum is governed by the laws of England and\n        Wales. The courts of England and Wales have exclusive\n        jurisdiction.\n\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nSIGNATURES\n───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nPROVIDER — Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd\n  Signature: __________________________\n  Print Name: Andrea Enning\n  Title: Director\n  Date: __________________________\n\nCUSTOMER — AFJ Cardiff Ltd\n  Signature: __________________________\n  Print Name: Plamedi [surname]\n  Title: Director\n  Date: __________________________\n```\n\n---\n\n## Sequencing — what to do in what order\n\n**Don't sign them all on the same day.** Sequence matters because each one depends on the previous:\n\n1. **Today — incorporate AFJ Cardiff Ltd** (via Companies House direct, £12, 24-hour turnaround). Don't sign anything until the Ltd exists — if Plamedi signs as a sole trader, all this paperwork becomes much messier to enforce.\n\n2. **Day 2 — sign the Mutual NDA first.** It's the lightest, sets the precedent, and protects both of you retroactively for the next 18 months of pre-existing WhatsApp/Drive/Gmail content.\n\n3. **Day 2 or 3 — sign the Consultancy Agreement + SLA + IP Assignment Addendum as one packet.** They go together. Get Professional Indemnity insurance for Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd **before signing** — because the moment you sign, you're exposed.\n\n4. **Day 3 onward — open Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd's Ltd business bank account** (Monzo Business, Starling, or HSBC Kinetic). Move the £0 retainer invoicing onto it even though the retainer is zero — you want the paper trail so when fees start in month 13, the bank has the history.\n\n5. **Day 3 onward — you start working \"under contract.\"** Anything you build from this point automatically belongs to AFJ Cardiff Ltd under the IP Assignment clause 1.1.\n\n---\n\n## Things to double-check before signing\n\n- **Plamedi's Companies House director code** — she'll get one when AFJ Cardiff Ltd is incorporated. She signs with that.\n- **Your SIC code** on Companies House — use **62020** (Information technology consultancy activities) for Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd. Don't use 62012 (Business and domestic software development) — it triggers different VAT and insurance classifications.\n- **PI insurance certificate** — get one from Hiscox / PolicyBee / Markel. £400–£600/year for £1m cover. Email it to Plamedi before signing day.\n- **Welsh language** — if either of you wants the documents in Welsh, the Welsh Government's standard Welsh translations are fine. Common Paper is English-only but a certified Welsh translation is ~£60/page.\n- **Stiwdio Newport** — once signed, send Millie (or whoever your contact is) a 3-line email: *\"Andrea Kwabena Technologies Ltd has been formally engaged by AFJ Cardiff Ltd to provide fractional CTO and platform architecture services. PI-insured, contracted, IP-assigned.\"* That's it. Now Stiwdio has the institutional language to back you up on grant applications.\n\n---\n\nWant me to also write the **Director's Resolution** for AFJ Cardiff Ltd (the one Companies House needs to formally appoint you, if that's the direction you go), and the **Conflict of Interest declaration** that goes with it?",
